aws::graph::propositions: # Helicopter Accident Due to Fuel Exhaustion
The accident occurred in Decorah, Iowa.
The accident occurred on September 30, 2012, at 09:20 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a MCDONNELL DOUGLAS HELI CO 369FF helicopter.
The defining event of the accident was loss of total engine power.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Positioning.
The accident number was CEN12LA667.
The helicopter registration was N530KD.
The helicopter sustained substantial damage.
There were 2 occupants in the helicopter.
No injuries occurred to any occupants.
The pilot and passenger were repositioning the helicopter.
The pilot stopped twice to refuel during the repositioning flight.
The pilot topped off the fuel tank at each of the first two stops.
During the second stop, the pilot used the helicopter for personal reasons.
The pilot flew for just over an hour during the personal use.
Before continuing the repositioning flight, the pilot added 15 gallons of fuel.
The 15 gallons was not enough fuel to top off the tank.
The pilot referenced the fuel gauge after adding the 15 gallons.
The fuel gauge indicated 305-310 pounds of fuel on board.
The pilot and passenger departed on the next leg of their flight.
The fuel-low caution light illuminated approximately 58 minutes after departure.
The fuel-low caution light should indicate 35 pounds of fuel remaining.
The pilot continued the flight after the fuel-low caution light illuminated.
The pilot was within a few miles of the destination airport when the light illuminated.
The engine quit approximately three minutes after the fuel-low caution light illuminated.
The pilot made an autorotation to a mature corn field.
The helicopter bounced upon touchdown.
The helicopter rolled over onto its left side after bouncing.
The rollover damaged the tail boom of the helicopter.
Examination of the helicopter revealed only two drops of fuel were drained from the fuel sump.
Examination revealed a 1/4-cup of fuel was drained from the fuel tank.
Further examination revealed no mechanical deficiencies with the fuel system.
Testing showed the fuel gauge was not calibrated correctly.
The fuel gauge indicated a higher fuel total than what was actually in the fuel tank.
Testing showed the fuel-low caution light was not calibrated correctly.
The fuel-low caution light activated when there was only 19 pounds of fuel in the tank.
The fuel-low caution light should have activated when there were 35 pounds of fuel in the tank.
According to the operator, the fuel-low caution light was inspected several months before the accident.
The inspection of the fuel-low caution light was part of a normal maintenance inspection.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Decorah, Iowa

## Date & Time: 
September 30, 2012, 09:20 Local

## Aircraft:
MCDONNELL DOUGLAS HELI CO 369FF

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (total)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Positioning

## Accident Number:
CEN12LA667

## Registration:
N530KD

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
2 None

## Analysis

The pilot and his passenger were repositioning the helicopter and stopped twice to refuel. Each time they stopped the pilot topped off the fuel tank. During the second stop, the pilot used the airplane for personal reasons and flew for just over an hour. Before continuing on with the repositioning flight, the pilot added 15 gallons of fuel. Since this was not enough fuel to top off the tank, he referenced the fuel guage, which indicated 305-310 pounds of fuel on board. The pilot and passenger then departed on the next leg of their flight. About 58 minutes after they departed, the fuel-low caution light illuminated, indicating there was 35 pounds of fuel remaining. The pilot continued with the flight since he was within a few miles of the destination airport. About three minutes after the fuel-low caution light illuminated, the engine quit. The pilot made an autorotation to a mature corn field. The helicopter bounced upon touch down and rolled over on to its left side, which damaged the tail boom. Examination of the helicopter revealed only two drops of fuel were drained from the fuel sump and a 1/4-cup of fuel was drained from the fuel tank. Further examination revealed no mechancal deficiencies with the fuel system; however, when the fuel gauge and low-fuel caution light were tested they were found to not be calibrated correctly. The fuel gauge indicated a higher fuel total then what was actually in the fuel tank and the fuel-low caution light came on when there was only 19 pounds of fuel in the fuel tank versus 35 pounds. According to the operator, the low fuel-low caution light was inspected several months before the accident as part of a normal maintenance inspection.
